<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1868-09-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1868-09-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="328" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d328">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Plumb</persName>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 98.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>,</placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1868-09-17"><hi rend="italic">September</hi> 17, 1868.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received your dispatch of the 12th
                            of August, No. 171. I entirely approve of the letter which, on the 7th
                            of August, you addressed to the Mexican minister for foreign affairs on
                            the subject of the recent ill treatment of citizens of the United States
                            at Monterey, by the authorities of that place.</p>
                        <p>The prompt and just reply of Mr. Azpiroz is satisfactory at the present
                            stage of the proceeding. The development will be awaited with much
                            interest.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Edward L. Plumb</hi>, Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>